# **Automation**

## **INFRASTRUCTURE AS CODE (IAC)**

To work with AWS CloudFormation, it’s important that you understand how to work with CloudFormation templates. And to understand the templates, you need to know how to work with the major sections of a template. Though the Resources section is the only required part of the template, using only this section greatly limits the service’s functionality. Also, though the template sections can be in any order, it can be helpful to use a logical order that’s similar to what’s in the documentation.

If you feel overwhelmed when you try to understand the template sections and how to build a stack through the template, make sure you get some hands-on experience with AWS CloudFormation Designer. Designer is a graphic tool for creating, viewing, and modifying CloudFormation templates. With Designer, you can diagram your template resources by using a drag-and-drop interface. You can then further edit the details by using the integrated JSON and YAML editor.

![][image1]

AWS CloudFormation Designer can be a helpful tool regardless of your CloudFormation experience. In addition to the ability to visualize the template resources, Designer provides a simplified way to author and edit templates.For more information, see the following resources:

* [Template Anatomy](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/template-anatomy.html)

 for CloudFormation templates  
[Why Use Amazon CloudFormation Designer?](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/working-with-templates-cfn-designer-why.html)

## **AWS SERVERLESS APPLICATION MODEL (AWS SAM)**

When you work with the AWS Serverless Application Model (AWS SAM), you interact with two parts: first, the template specification; and second, the AWS SAM command line interface (CLI). The AWS SAM template specification is an extension of what you’re already familiar with: CloudFormation templates. You can use CloudFormation resources inside an AWS SAM template. You can also use a specific AWS SAM syntax to define resources that will expand into CloudFormation resources.

For more information about the specific resources for AWS SAM, see the [AWS SAM Resource and Property Reference](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/serverless-application-model/latest/developerguide/sam-specification-resources-and-properties.html)

 in the *AWS SAM Developer Guide*.You can use the AWS SAM CLI to initialize, build, and deploy your application, and more. The following AWS SAM template sample includes a definition for a simple Lambda function. The AWS SAM CLI will build and package the function code, and send the AWS SAM template to CloudFormation to create a stack. Because the template specifies a transform, CloudFormation expands the shorthand definitions from AWS SAM into the final resources. The following template also doesn’t define a role. Instead, when the shorthand AWS SAM syntax is expanded, AWS SAM creates a sensible default role.

*AWSTemplateFormatVersion: '2010-09-09'*

*Transform: AWS::Serverless-2016-10-31*

*Description: first-sam*

*Resources:*

*HelloWorld Function:*

*Type: AWS::Serverless::Function*

*Properties:*

*CodeUri: hello\_world/*

*Handler: hello.lambda\_handler*

*Runtime: python3.9*

You can also use the SAM shorthand notation to create AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) policies from common templates. This feature is convenient because it abstracts all the resources that you need to explicitly create in a CloudFormation template. For more information, see [AWS SAM Policy Templates](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/serverless-application-model/latest/developerguide/serverless-policy-templates.html)

.

## **AWS AMPLIFY**

In addition to the traditional AWS documentation, AWS also provides a location called the *Amplify Dev Center* to help you understand and use AWS Amplify. The Amplify Dev Center provides a consolidated location for accessing targeted and specific documentation, guides for getting started, tutorials and courses for building with Amplify, the Amplify UI Library, and more. This location can help you start your journey towards understanding and using AWS Amplify as you move forward.For more information, see the [Amplify Dev Center](https://docs.amplify.aws/)
